{"type":"message","id":"36448cd1","parentId":"b6836ecc","timestamp":"2026-03-01T00:18:36.595Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Discussing browsing options**\n\nI should respond concisely about free browsing options. Right now, the Brave search key isn't set up. Brave is free with an API key, but I should be clear that web_fetch is more for scraping HTML than actual browsing. OpenAI doesn't have default browsing capabilities.\n\nI can suggest alternatives like using public search APIs that may require keys, but also recommend Chrome extensions or manual searches. If they want a browsing-like experience for a few requests, I can fetch specific URLs directly without needing a search index. I'll offer these options and ask what they prefer!","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"text","text":"Short answer: yes, you can get browsing-like capabilities for free, but with some limits.\n\nOptions you can use now\n- Direct URL fetch (no search engine): Use web_fetch to pull a specific page (markdown/text extraction). Great for on-demand reading of a known source, no API keys required.\n- Local/brief search without a paid API: You can paste a few search results you care about and I can summarize or extract quotes, but I won’t have live, broad searching without a provider/key.\n- Free-tier search APIs (with keys): Some providers offer free tiers (e.g., SerpAPI, others). They still require API keys, and limits apply, but they’re usable for small projects.\n- Official browser extensions or tools: If you just need a browsing-like workflow, browser-based tools or manual checks might be simpler and free.\n\nWhat I can do right now\n- If you want real-time research on a topic, give me a few target URLs or topics and I’ll fetch and summarize them using web_fetch.\n- If you’re comfortable providing a Brave/Branded key, I can set up Brave Search with a free-tier key and show you how to test it.\n- I can draft a low-cost or free MVP for a “su