{"type":"message","id":"055603d8","parentId":"f3b618d6","timestamp":"2026-03-01T00:30:12.200Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Explaining model routing**\n\nI need to provide a high-level explanation of model routing without digging into internal logs. This should involve discussing cheaper models for drafting, optimizing prompts, caching, context windows, thresholds, and fallback strategies. I should ask for any preferences to tailor the explanation. There's no tool required for this. Additionally, I’ll offer a debugging plan that includes logging fields and ensuring deterministic routing and reproducibility. Finally, I can offer an audit of the current routing configuration while keeping everything concise.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"text","text":"Great question. I’ll lay out the high-level, deterministic approach I use for model routing (not random), plus how we can diagnose what you’re seeing in logs.\n\nHow routing currently should work (conceptual, deterministic)\n- Tiered routing: start with a cheaper/lower-cost model for drafting, simple tasks, and when a task requires deeper reasoning or external data, elevate to a higher-power model.\n- Decision criteria (not random):\n  - Task type: drafting/summary = cheap model; complex reasoning, code, or long-context tasks = higher-power model.\n  - Context size: if the current context + prompt fit comfortably in a small model’s window, use the cheap model.\n  - Output needs: if strict correctness or multi-step reasoning is needed, escalate.\n  - User preferences: any explicit setting to force a model or disable web access, etc.\n- Caching and re-use: if a similar prompt has been solved recently, reuse the prior result or summary to avoid re-querying a costly model.\n- Guardrails: if the cheap model returns an unsatisfactory result, optionally rerun with a higher-power model for refinement.\n- Token budgeting: track tokens used per step and pick the minimum model that still meets quality needs.\n\nWhat could cause the “random” impression in logs\n- Context variation: different incoming prompts, or prompts with slightly different phrasing, can trigger different routing paths.\n- Non-deterministic prompts: if prompts include optional flags or user-driven toggles, they can flip the path.\n- Cache misses: if a previous similar prompt isn’t in cache, we re-run with a higher-power model.\n- Runtime config drift: changes in enabled features (e.g., web search on/off, tool usage) can affect model choice.\n- Time-based or load-based heuristics: if a QoS safeguard temporarily prefers a different tier to balance throughput, logs might look inconsistent.\n- Logging gaps: if logs omit some fields or events, it can look like randomness even when routing is deterministic.\n\nHow we can debug and make it deterministic\n- Define a fixed routing policy: write down exact rules for when to use cheap vs. expensive models (e.g., if prompt length < X tokens and no web fetch needed, use cheap; else use expensive).\n- Instrumentation: log a small, structured summary for each call: prompt hash, context size, chosen model, rationale tag (e.g., “draft+cache” or “refine”).\n- Reproduce steps: provide a controlled test set of prompts and run them through the same policy to verify consistent choices.\n- Check for drift: compare current policy config with the last known good policy; ensure no automatic toggles are enabled by mistake.\n- If you can share a sample log snippet (with model names and the prompts), I can map it to the policy and identify where paths diverge.\n\nWhat I need from you to tighten this up\n- Do you want a strictly fixed policy (no surprises) or a policy that prefers speed but can degrade gracefully to accuracy when needed?\n- Which models do you want in the cheap-to-expensive ladder (e.g., a local/low-cost model first, then Claude/GPT-class as fallback)?\n- Are there any tasks you want explicitly forced to a particular model (e.g., always use the higher-power model for code tasks)?\n- Would you like a short, per-session log digest that shows which model was used and why, to audit routing?\n\nIf you’d like, I can draft a concrete routing policy (SKILL.md style) you can review, and we can add deterministic logging so the OpenRouter logs are no longer ambiguous."}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"openrouter/auto","usage":{"input":7566,"output":885,"cacheRead":12672,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":21123,"cost":{"input":-7566,"output":-885,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":-8451}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1772325003046}}
