{"type":"message","id":"1bc82bbd","parentId":"02577d64","timestamp":"2026-03-01T00:31:41.626Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Explaining routing decisions**\n\nI want to clarify that in this system, routing decisions come from the OpenRouter configuration and our local policy. The OpenRouter may handle auto-routing, while I can propose and log decisions. To achieve determinism, we should set a fixed policy, disable auto-routing, and specify models. I can also draft a routing policy document. So, the routing is influenced by the OpenRouter setup, and I recommend implementing a clear policy with hooks for logging. Let's go ahead and respond!","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"text","text":"Short answer: both, but OpenRouter largely decides based on its configured routing rules, while I can suggest or enforce a policy and log the rationale.\n\n- OpenRouter side: uses its internal routing logic to pick a model (cheap vs. expensive) based on defaults, your config, and any active features (web, tools, context size, etc.).\n- My side: I can apply a deterministic routing policy, tag each decision, and push for logs that show the chosen model and rationale. If you want zero randomness, we should lock in exact rules and disable any opportunistic fallbacks.\n\nIf you’d like, I can draft a concrete, fixed routing policy (SKILL.md style) and a deterministic logging plan so you can audit every decision."}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"openrouter/auto","usage":{"input":8361,"output":445,"cacheRead":12800,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":21606,"cost":{"input":-8361,"output":-445,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":-8806}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1772325096016}}
