{"type":"message","id":"7db42488","parentId":"e861ef2f","timestamp":"2026-03-01T14:08:16.587Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Addressing email rejection issues**\n\nI need to help the user address the email deliverability rejection they reported. I'd suggest they check local policies, and important settings like SPF, DKIM, and DMARC. I can propose steps such as verifying their MX records and settings for sending from localhost (127.0.0.1), which might indicate a local mail server issue. I'll outline a brief checklist for them and offer to run checks or send a test email. A quick workaround could be sending from their usual Gmail address instead. Let’s get started with actionable steps!","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"text","text":"That 550 5.7.1 from localhost means your mail server is rejecting the message at the gateway level due to local policy. A quick check and fix plan:\n\nWhat to check and fix\n- Sending domain and origin\n  - Confirm the From address you’re using is allowed by your mail gateway (not localhost). If you’re sending from 127.0.0.1, many gateways treat it as unauthenticated.\n- SPF, DKIM, DMARC\n  - Ensure the sending host/domain is listed in SPF records and that DKIM signatures are being applied. If you’re relaying through a local MTA, you may need to configure it to use your domain’s SMTP server with proper SPF/DKIM.\n- Relay / gateway rules\n  - Check if there is a local policy blocking messages from the OpenClaw host or from a “brandless”/test sender. You may need an approved relay or a neutral, whitelisted sender.\n- Content/attachments\n  - Some mail gateways block messages that look like automated tests or that lack typical headers. A minimal body with a known subject can help.\n\nPractical next steps\n- Try sending from a trusted, whitelisted Gmail/organization address (not the local 127.0.0.1 path) to see if the digest can land in your inbox.\n- If you must keep using the OpenClaw path, configure a proper SMTP relay that’s allowed by your gateway and ensure SPF/DKIM are set up for that relay.\n- Grab the exact bounce text (you posted the header, but the full bounce message sometimes includes a reason code). If you share more of the bounce details, I can diagnose more precisely.\n\nImmediate options\n- I can draft a minimal, branding-free test email that uses a whitelisted SMTP path (if you provide an allowed relay or domain), and attempt delivery again.\n- Or, we can switch to a local preview file (Markdown) for review, until the mail route is fixed.\n\nHow would you like to proceed? If you can share any additional bounce text or tell me which SMTP/relay you’re allowed to use, I’ll tailor the fix."}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"openrouter/auto","usage":{"input":51816,"output":754,"cacheRead":1792,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":54362,"cost":{"input":-51816,"output":-754,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":-52570}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1772374089828}}
